\begin_layout Standard
We have a population of 
\shape italic
risk averse
\shape default
 expected utility maximizing consumers.
 These consumers move second and they accept or reject a firm's offer.
 A representative consumer has wealth equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

; probability of losing 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\left\{ G,B\right\} $
\end_inset

, and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{G}<p_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

G
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is for a good type of consumer with low risk of loss and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

B
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is a bad type of consumer with a high risk of loss.
 Assume that the probability of the consumer being a good type is equal
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, which means that the average risk (or pooled level of risk) is equal to
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{p}=\lambda p_{G}+(1-\lambda)p_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Further assume that the expected utility of a consumer of type 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is equal to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
U_{i}=p_{i}\cdot u(consumption\, in\, s_{2})+(1-p_{i})\cdot u(consumption\, in\, s_{1}),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}$
\end_inset

 denotes the level of consumption in State 1 where there is no loss; and
 level of consumption in State 2 where there is a loss, respectively.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $u'(\cdot)>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u''(\cdot)<0$
\end_inset

 for simplicity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What have we just assumed here?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The level of risk aversion is equal for both good and bad types of consumers.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Recall our measures of risk aversion from Econ 2020a, and convince yourself.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We have the same utility function in both the loss state (State 2) and the
 no loss state (State 1).
 
\end_layout

