\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

M
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 denotes the premium, and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

R
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 denotes the reimbursement amount.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the demand and supply side together we have the following trivial
 results:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A consumer of type 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\left\{ G,B\right\} $
\end_inset

 who has purchased insurance will consume, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}=W-M-L+R$
\end_inset

 in State 2 and with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-p_{i}$
\end_inset

 she will consume 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}=W-M$
\end_inset

 in State 1.
 Without insurance, consumption is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2,no\, insurance}=W-L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1,no\, insurance}=W$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Note that consumption in each state is completely defined by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

M
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

R
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 a firm who has sold insurance will have payoff equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $M-R$
\end_inset

 in State 2 and with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-p_{i}$
\end_inset

 it will have payoff equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 in State 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The firms' expected profit can be written as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\mathbb{E}\left[\pi\right] & = & p_{i}(M-R)+(1-p_{i})(M)\nonumber \\
 & = & p_{i}(W-L-s_{2})+(1-p_{i})(W-s_{1})\nonumber \\
 & = & \left(W-p_{i}L\right)-\left(p_{i}s_{2}+(1-p_{i})s_{1}\right)\label{Expected Profit in s1 and s2}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the first term is equal to the uninsured expected consumption and
 the second term is equal to the insured expected consumption.
 This can be rewritten in a more convenient form as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
s_{2}=-\frac{\left(1-p_{i}\right)}{p_{i}}s_{1}+\frac{1}{p_{i}}\cdot\left\{ \left(W-p_{i}L\right)-\mathbb{E}\left[\pi\right]\right\} \label{Linear Expected Profit in s1 and s2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Do you see why the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sun
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is in the lower left hand corner when we draw the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[s_{1},s_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 Euclidean plane?
\end_layout

