\end_inset

 in Figure III.
 We solve by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}=s_{2}=s$
\end_inset

, and we find that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
s=1100-s\Rightarrow s=s_{1}=s_{2}=750\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, we can use 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\vec{s}_{p}=\left[750,\,750\right]$
\end_inset

 to solve for the premium and the redistribution (since we know 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

).
 This in turn fully identifies the pooling insurance contract 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\kappa}_{p}=\left[M_{p},\, R_{p}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Non-Existence of Pooling Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I use a graphical argument to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\vec{s}_{p}=\left[750,\,750\right]$
\end_inset

 is not a pooling equilibrium despite satisfying the conditions above.
 Consider the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

, which we can further write as 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=\left[s_{1\varepsilon},s_{2\varepsilon}\right]$
\end_inset

 in Figure III.
 If an insurer were to offer this consumption bundle, the good type consumer
 would prefer 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=\left[s_{1\varepsilon},s_{2\varepsilon}\right]$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}_{p}=\left[750,\,750\right]$
\end_inset

 because of the single crossing principle.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=\left[s_{1\varepsilon},s_{2\varepsilon}\right]$
\end_inset

 is below the pooled actuarily fair/zero profit line 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{AP}$
\end_inset

, which means that the insurer can make positive profits if they were to
 offer this contract.
 Because of what I (re)emphasized at the beginning of this section on pooling
 equilibrium, the immediate result is that there does not exist a pooling
 equilibrium.
 This is Main Result 2.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also note that because 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}_{p}=\left[750,\,750\right]$
\end_inset

 lies below the indifference curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{U}_{G}$
\end_inset

, which passes through the separating equilibrium 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{G}$
\end_inset

, the good types do not prefer the pooling consumption bundle to the separating
 equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Pooling Equilibrium (with high 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Actuarily Fair Line and the Pooling Equilibrium with high 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that there are a lot of good types and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0.95,$
\end_inset

 we can solve for the pooled probability of state 2 occurring: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\bar{p}'=\lambda p_{G}+(1-\lambda)p_{B}=\left(0.95\times0.1\right)+\left(0.05\times0.6\right)=\frac{1}{8}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Expected Profit in s1 and s2"

\end_inset

 (or equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Linear Expected Profit in s1 and s2"

\end_inset

), we can write the actuarily fair line for pooled contracts (
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{AP'}$
\end_inset

) as follows: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\left(W-\bar{p}'L\right)-\left(\bar{p}'s_{2}+(1-\bar{p}')\cdot s_{1}\right) & = & 0\nonumber \\
\Rightarrow\left(1000-\left(\frac{1}{8}\cdot900\right)\right)-\left(\frac{1}{8}\cdot s_{2}+(1-0.5)\cdot s_{1}\right) & = & 0\nonumber \\
\Rightarrow s_{2}=7100-7s_{1}\label{eq:AP'}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Note that the slope of the actuarily fair line for the bad type is equal
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{1-\bar{p}'}{\bar{p}'}=-\frac{\frac{7}{8}}{\frac{1}{8}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now using equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AP'"

\end_inset

, we can solve for the full insurance, zero-profit point for the pooled
 contract, or point 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

' in Figure III.
 We solve by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}=s_{2}=s$
\end_inset

, and we find that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
s=7100-8s\Rightarrow s=s_{1}=s_{2}=887.5\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, we can use 
\begin_inset Formula $P'=\vec{s}_{p'}=\left[887.5,\,887.5\right]$
\end_inset

 to solve for the premium and the redistribution (since we know 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

).
 This in turn fully identifies the pooling insurance contract 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\kappa}_{p'}=\left[M_{p},\, R_{p}\right]$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0.95$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Non-Existence of Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumption bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $P'=\vec{s}_{p'}=\left[887.5,\,887.5\right]$
\end_inset

 is preferred by the good type to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{G}$
\end_inset

, so if we had contracts 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{G}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{B}$
\end_inset

, a firm could make positive profits by offering a contract like 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 The result is that there is no equilibrium, which is equivalent to Main
 Result 3.
 
\end_layout

